Cook,<br><br>
If your *orders* were not to stop under any circumstances. You don't stop.<br><br>
The winter soldier testimony was given by soldiers who believed that their words would bring to light what they had seen in Vietnam. Whether or not *they* perceived *themselves* as being used by &quot;communists&quot;, I can't say.<br><br>
But, to dismiss their testimony as &quot;hearsay&quot; or &quot;exaggerations&quot; effectively undercuts every bit of information that *all* Vietnam vets have to relate about their experiences. Even the good stuff.<br><br>
We had rules of engagement and we had orders that we followed. There were times that I had to make very difficult decisions like the one you described above. Likewise time and circumstances were a tremendous factor. Things done in the heat of battle can't be second guessed.<br><br>
Go back and read the testimony and you will find many testimonies that had nothing to do with soldiers involved in the type of situation that you have described - or any life threatening situation.<br><br>

